		<p>Pennyweight is a standard unit of measurement used in the precious met=
als industry. It originated as a unit of the troy weight system in 15th Cen=
tury England and remains the standard for valuing precious metals today.Dur=
ing 15th Century England, the weight of an English penny was exactly 1/20th=
 of a troy ounce and 1/240th of a troy pound of sterling silver. Therefore,=
 there are 20 pennyweights in a troy ounce and 12 troy ounces in a troy pou=
nd.</p>
<p>Although the same grain is used in both the troy weight system and the m=
ore common avoirdupois system (used in the United States), a troy ounce is =
heavier than an avoirdupois ounce, and a troy pound is lighter than an avoi=
rdupois pound. There are 20 pennyweights in a troy ounce, compared to 31.1 =
grams in a troy ounce.</p>
<p>With prices set per troy ounce by the London fix, calculating a pennywei=
ght price on the spot can be tricky. To help, we=E2=80=99ve provided our pe=
nnyweight calculator and conversion chart below. Use these tools to help de=
termine the value of your precious metals.</p>
			</div>
